Gemini said
Updating the BIOS on your Framework 13 (Intel Core Ultra Series 1) is fairly straightforward, but the "best" approach depends on whether you're running Windows or Linux.

As of early 2026, the current stable version for your model is typically 3.06 (though you should always check the Framework BIOS page for newer releases).

⚡ Essential Pre-flight Checklist
Before starting any of the methods below:

Plug in your charger: The update will likely refuse to start (or could fail catastrophically) if you are on battery power.

Check your current version: Restart and tap F2 to enter BIOS and see your version.

Note: Some updates (like 3.06) require you to be on a specific previous version (like 3.04) first. If you are far behind, you may need to update in steps.

Disable BitLocker: If you are on Windows, suspend BitLocker protection before starting to avoid being locked out.

🛠️ Method 1: Windows (The Easiest)
If you have Windows installed, this is the most seamless "double-click and done" method.

Download the Windows Installer (.exe) from the Framework support site.

Run the .exe as an Administrator.

Click Yes to the reboot prompt.

Do not touch the laptop while the progress bar moves. It will reboot automatically once finished.

Important: For the Ultra Series, you may need to run the installer a second time after the reboot to update the Retimer firmware (which controls your ports).

🐧 Method 2: Linux (The Recommended)
Framework has excellent Linux support. You have two main paths:

Option A: LVFS (The Pro Way)
Most modern distros (Ubuntu, Fedora, Mint) support the Linux Vendor Firmware Service.

Open your terminal and run:

Bash
fwupdmgr refresh
fwupdmgr get-updates
fwupdmgr update
If an update is available, follow the prompts and reboot.

Option B: EFI Shell (The "Universal" Way)
Use this if LVFS isn't working or if you prefer a "clean" update outside the OS.

Download the EFI Shell Update (.zip).

Format a USB drive to FAT32.

Extract the contents of the zip directly to the root of the USB drive.

Plug the USB into your Framework, reboot, and tap F12 repeatedly.

Select the USB drive. The startup.nsh script should run automatically and begin the update.

⚠️ Troubleshooting Common Issues
Black Screen: During the update, the screen may go black for 1–2 minutes. This is normal. Do not force power off.

Ports not working after update: If a port stops recognizing devices, shut down the laptop, unplug the power, wait 90 seconds, and then plug back in and boot. This resets the PD (Power Delivery) controllers.

"Security Violation" on EFI Update: If the USB won't boot, you may need to enter BIOS (F2) and temporarily disable Secure Boot.

