1. Install the tools
Open your terminal and grab the necessary packages:

Bash
sudo pacman -S fwupd
2. Configure for Framework
Once installed, you need to start the daemon and refresh the database. Because Framework sometimes keeps newer BIOS versions in a "testing" state before full stable release, you might need to enable the testing remote if the update doesn't show up immediately.

Start the service:

Bash
sudo systemctl start fwupd
Refresh the metadata:

Bash
fwupdmgr refresh --force
Check for the BIOS:

Bash
fwupdmgr get-updates
[!TIP]
If no BIOS update is found: Framework often lists Ultra Series updates in the "testing" channel first. You can enable it with:
fwupdmgr enable-remote lvfs-testing
Then run the refresh again.

3. Apply the Update
If it finds the update:

Plug in your charger.

Run: fwupdmgr update

Type y to agree to the reboot.

Arch will schedule the update. When you reboot, you'll see a black screen with a progress bar. Do not power off.

🛠️ The "Arch Manual" Fallback (EFI Shell)
If fwupd gives you trouble (Arch can be picky with EFI partition mounting), the EFI Shell method is the most "bulletproof" for Linux users:

Grab a USB drive and format it to FAT32.

Download the Linux/Other (EFI Shell) zip from the Framework Ultra 7 Support Page.

Unzip everything to the USB.

Reboot, tap F12, select the USB.

It will launch a script. It might update the Retimers first, reboot, and then you'll need to boot from the USB again to finish the actual BIOS.

