To automate this on Arch, you don't actually need to write any custom scripts. The fwupd package already provides a built-in timer that handles the background metadata refresh.

Here is how you set it up to keep your system aware of new stable updates without you having to manually check.

🕒 Enable the fwupd-refresh Timer
This timer runs a service that downloads the latest metadata from LVFS (the stable channel) so that when you do run fwupdmgr get-updates, the information is already there and ready.

Enable and start the timer:

Bash
sudo systemctl enable --now fwupd-refresh.timer
Verify it's scheduled:

Bash
systemctl list-timers --all | grep fwupd
[!NOTE]
By default, this runs once every 24 hours. It won't install anything automatically (which is good—you don't want your BIOS updating while you're in the middle of a project), but it will ensure your local database is current.

🛠️ The "Arch Way" (Optional): Update Notifications
If you want to be notified in your terminal or desktop when an update is actually found by that background timer, you have two cool options:

1. The MOTD (Message of the Day)
If you use a terminal frequently, you can have it tell you if updates are waiting when you log in.

Edit /etc/fwupd/fwupd.conf.

Ensure ShowDeviceNotifications=true is set.

This usually integrates with the system MOTD on many distros, though on Arch you might need to check the fwupd-refresh.service logs to see results.

2. Desktop Notifications (GNOME/KDE)
If you are running a desktop environment like GNOME or KDE Plasma, you don't even need the systemd timer manually.

GNOME: Uses gnome-software to check in the background.

KDE: Uses the Discover backend.

Since you're on Arch, you'd just need to install the package packagekit-qt6 (for KDE) or gnome-software to get GUI notifications.

